{"id":14881063,"mediaExerciseId":"8d2ea01e-9d33-44a8-8064-f5792a392e1d","exerciseName":"14","chapterName":"7","chapterTitle":"Interest Rates and Bond Valuation","groupId":612313,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":234,"solutions":[{"id":5968197,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This task asks **to determine the inflation following the given data.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":30,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/032027b11a0326cc70d755d6983ab023/lateximg_large.png","width":935},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/032027b11a0326cc70d755d6983ab023/lateximg.png","width":468}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"For this calculation, we will use the Fisher effect. The Fisher effect tells us the correlation between the nominal return, real return, and rising prices(inflation). Investors are always willing to invest in a security with a positive actual return. The only way for the investor to invest in the negative return of a bond will be in the time of deflation. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":174,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/b1b1b63184b1b9274470856dbe89845c/lateximg_large.png","width":1075},"regular":{"height":88,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/b1b1b63184b1b9274470856dbe89845c/lateximg.png","width":537}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The formula for the Fisher effect is as follows:\n\n$$1+\\text{R}=\\left(1+\\text{r}\\right)\\times\\left(1+\\text{h}\\right)$$\n\nR- the nominal return\nr- the real return\nh- inflation effect","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":154,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/2426a1d119dfa9f0d57ceed0457c4aa4/lateximg_large.png","width":764},"regular":{"height":78,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/2426a1d119dfa9f0d57ceed0457c4aa4/lateximg.png","width":383}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's insert the given data in the formula previous formula.\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n1+\\text{h}&=\\dfrac{\\left(1+R\\right)}{\\left(1+\\text{r}\\right)}\\\\[15pt]\n&=\\dfrac{1+12.3\\%}{1+8\\%}-1\\\\[15pt]\n&=0.0398\\times100\\\\[15pt]\n&=3.98\\%\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\n**Janice will calculate that the inflation rate is 3.98\\%.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":476,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/baa1ba87860355eeabdfe7a56fffe3ae/lateximg_large.png","width":785},"regular":{"height":240,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/e1dd40d41c4b27a891377fca5f2a5fdf/baa1ba87860355eeabdfe7a56fffe3ae/lateximg.png","width":392}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"e6abf174-097f-49dc-8121-87177c345801","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjec